    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "thanks that helps. so when you say they aren't fixed until they're measured, is that what einstein was talking about when he called it \"spooky action at a distance\"? why did he find it so unsettling?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Yes, that \"spooky action at a distance\" is exactly what Einstein was grappling with! He found it unsettling because it seemed to violate the principle of locality—the idea that an object can only be influenced by its immediate surroundings. For Einstein, this instantaneous connection between distant particles suggested some kind of hidden communication or influence traveling faster than the speed of light, which, in his view, was fundamentally impossible. It felt like some sort of magical, non-local connection, which is a concept that truly unnerves a traditional, clockwork-universe thinker.",
